{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507731"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:56:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:56:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2664"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2664"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.05,0.03,0.71,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2664"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61579"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2664"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2664"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47032"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1209"},{"type":"tags","id":"1210"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5815"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42540"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61579"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after being bitten by a brown snake while hiking. He kicked the snake and ran before collapsing. Other hikers found him minutes later with disorientation, slurred speech, and muscle weakness. Emergency services applied a pressure bandage from his right toes to mid-shin, covering the bite site on his right ankle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. He has ptosis, respiratory distress, and flaccid muscle tone. He has received initial fluid resuscitation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Baseline laboratory investigations (FBE, UEC, LFT\u0027s, CK and coagulation studies)","Swab bite site for venom detection","Release the pressure bandage immobilisation","Administer intravenous polyvalent antivenom","Continuous monitoring of vital signs and neurological status"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clear clinical evidence of snake envenomation, demonstrating neurotoxicity (ptosis, respiratory distress) and potential myotoxicity (flaccid tone). Given these life-threatening features, immediate treatment is essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister intravenous polyvalent antivenom\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. When there are clear signs of systemic envenomation, antivenom administration should not be delayed. While specific antivenom would be ideal, polyvalent antivenom is appropriate when the exact snake species is uncertain or toxicology advice is not immediately available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBaseline laboratory investigations\u003C/strong\u003E, while important, should not delay antivenom administration when clinical envenomation is evident. These tests help confirm envenomation and monitor for complications but are secondary to immediate life-saving treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwab bite site\u003C/strong\u003E for venom detection can help identify the snake species but is not a priority when clinical envenomation is already evident and should not delay antivenom administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelease the pressure bandage\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate at this stage as it could lead to rapid systemic absorption of remaining venom. The bandage should only be removed after antivenom administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E is essential but should occur concurrently with, not before, antivenom administration. The patient requires close observation for at least 12 hours post-bite and after antivenom administration to monitor for ongoing envenomation and potential adverse reactions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clinical features of brown snake envenomation include neurotoxicity, coagulopathy, and myotoxicity requiring immediate antivenom administration.","Pressure immobilisation bandaging should not be released until after antivenom administration in confirmed envenomation.","Laboratory investigations are important but should not delay antivenom administration in clinically evident envenomation."],"references":["Geoffrey K Isbister, Simon G A Brown, Colin B Page, David L McCoubrie, Shaun L Greene and Nicholas A Buckley Med J Aust 2013; 199 (11): 763-768. || doi: 10.5694/mja12.11172 Published online: 16 December 2013","Ireland G, Brown SG, Buckley NA, et al. Changes in serial laboratory test results in snakebite patients: when can we safely exclude envenoming? Med J Aust 2010; 193: 285-290."]},